This amendment records structural changes to the constitutional filesystem layout and introduces the founding document and filename-state model. It supersedes the filesystem layout rules in amendment 20260209105816.

All constitutional files encode state in their filename suffix (emoji only, no `.md` extension). State transitions are deterministic renames performed by scripts, not agents.

Filename-state model:

- Amendments: `timestamp.ğŸ“` (draft), `timestamp.âœ…` (accepted)
- Founding document: `FOUNDING.ğŸ“` (draft), `FOUNDING.â³` (under review), `FOUNDING.âœ…` (accepted as grundnorm)
- Law: `LAW.âœ…` (active), `LAW.â³` (resolving), `LAW.âŒ` (corrupted)

Filesystem layout (supersedes prior layout rules):

- `.constitution/amendments/` SHALL store constitutional amendments (renamed from `.articles/`).
- `.constitution/FOUNDING.ğŸ“` (or `.â³` or `.âœ…`) SHALL store the founding document at the `.constitution/` root.
- `.constitution/LAW.âœ…` (or `.â³` or `.âŒ`) SHALL store derived law at the `.constitution/` root.
- `skill/scripts/` SHALL store constitutional procedures and enforcement scripts.
- `skill/resources/` SHALL store constitutional agent prompts.
- Draft amendment records SHALL use filename form `timestamp.ğŸ“`.
- Accepted amendment records SHALL use filename form `timestamp.âœ…`.
- File extensions are emoji suffixes only (no `.md`).

The founding document is the constitutional grundnorm:

- The founding document is the axiomatic presupposition that makes the amendment system intelligible.
- There is no law before the founding document is accepted. Accepting the founding document triggers initial law creation.
- The founding document participates in amendments hash computation. `FOUNDING.âœ…` is included first (before amendments) in the hash.
- Once accepted (`FOUNDING.âœ…`), the founding document is immutable.
- Founding suitability evaluation uses criteria appropriate to a grundnorm (coherence, minimality, grounding, stability). Ambiguity tolerance is explicitly higher than for amendments.
- Law derivation agents SHALL read `FOUNDING.âœ…` as baseline context before processing amendments.

State transition ownership (all deterministic script renames):

- `LAW.âœ…` to `LAW.â³`: `promote_article.py` (amendment accepted) or `hook_pre_tool_use.py` (hash drift)
- `LAW.â³` to `LAW.âœ…`: `sync_article_hash.py` (reconciliation succeeds)
- `LAW.*` to `LAW.âŒ`: `verify_kernel_hash.py` (malformed file)
- `FOUNDING.ğŸ“` to `FOUNDING.â³`: `apply_founding_result.py` (APPLY_OK)
- `FOUNDING.â³` to `FOUNDING.ğŸ“`: `apply_founding_result.py` (NEEDS_INPUT)
- `FOUNDING.â³` to `FOUNDING.âœ…`: `promote_founding.py` (evaluation passed)
- `timestamp.ğŸ“` to `timestamp.âœ…`: `promote_article.py` (review passed)

Hash computation:

- Constitutional hash SHALL be computed from `FOUNDING.âœ…` (first, if it exists) followed by accepted amendments (`*.âœ…` in `.constitution/amendments/`).
- Amendment frontmatter SHALL be excluded from hash input.
- Hash input SHALL be the trimmed markdown body.

Operational definitions (updated):

- Constitutional acceptance procedure means running `skill/scripts/promote_article.py` on a draft amendment in `status: review` with matching `apply_ok_at`.
- Law reconciliation means updating `LAW.â³` content, then running `skill/scripts/sync_article_hash.py` to restamp and rename to `LAW.âœ…`.
- Verification means running `skill/scripts/verify_kernel_hash.py` and requiring `RESULT=PASS`.
